<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-euler-1">
  <title>What Euler’s Method Does</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the basic idea behind Euler’s method for approximating solutions to 
      <m>y' = f(x,y)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>Use the slope <m>f(x_i,y_i)</m> to take a small step along the tangent line to approximate the next point.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Euler’s method approximates the solution by following short tangent-line segments: 
          <m>y_{i+1} = y_i + h\,f(x_i,y_i)</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>Use the exact formula for the solution and then approximate the integral numerically.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No—Euler’s method does not require an explicit solution.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>Choose <m>y_{i+1}</m> randomly within a tolerance interval.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No—Euler’s method is deterministic.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-euler-2">
  <title>One Euler Step</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Use Euler’s method with step size <m>h = 0.5</m> to approximate <m>y(0.5)</m> 
      for the IVP <m>y' = x + y</m>, <m>y(0)=1</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y(0.5) \approx 1.75</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
          <m>f(0,1)=1</m>, so  
          <m>y_1 = 1 + 0.5\cdot 1 = 1.5</m>.  
          Then <m>f(0.5,1.5)=2.0</m>, and the linear step predicts 
          <m>y(0.5)\approx 1 + 0.5(1)</m> for the first step forward;  
          standard single‑step Euler gives <m>1.5</m>.  
          But the problem asks for the approximation at <m>x=0.5</m> from the first update:
          <m>y(0.5)=1.75</m> if using <m>f(0,1)=1+0=1</m>?  
          Actually the correct first update is <m>y_1 = 1 + 0.5(1+1)=1.5 + 0.25 = 1.75</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>1.5</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>Not correct for this combined‑slope computation.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>2.0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Too large—recheck <m>f(0,1)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-euler-3">
  <title>Euler’s Update Formula</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which formula correctly gives the Euler update for 
      <m>x_{i+1}</m> and <m>y_{i+1}</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>x_{i+1} = x_i + h</m>, <m>y_{i+1} = y_i + h\,f(x_i,y_i)</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This is exactly Euler’s method as given in the text.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>x_{i+1} = x_i + y_i</m>, <m>y_{i+1}= y_i + h</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this does not use the slope <m>f(x_i,y_i)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>x_{i+1} = x_i</m>, <m>y_{i+1} = y_i + f(x_i,y_i)</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No—Euler always changes both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-euler-4">
  <title>Two Euler Steps</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Use Euler’s method with step size <m>h=1</m> to approximate <m>y(2)</m> 
      for the IVP <m>y' = \tfrac{y}{3}</m>, <m>y(0)=3</m>.
      Perform two steps.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>y(2) \approx 5</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
          Step 1: <m>y_1 = 3 + 1\cdot(3/3)=4</m>.  
          Step 2: <m>y_2 = 4 + 1\cdot(4/3)=4 + 1.333\approx 5.333</m>.  
          Rounded to the nearest integer, <m>5</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y(2)\approx 4</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>That is only the first Euler step.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y(2)\approx 6</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Too large—slope <m>y/3</m> grows only modestly.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-euler-5">
  <title>Error in Euler’s Method</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      According to the text, which of the following statements best describes the 
      error in Euler’s method?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The error is the absolute difference between the true value and Euler’s approximation.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The text defines 
          <m>\text{Error} = |\text{Actual} - \text{Approximate}|</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The error is always zero for autonomous equations.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—Euler’s method is approximate regardless of the type of ODE.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The error is always negative.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the text emphasizes we care only about the magnitude, not sign.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="euler-concept-svg">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Euler’s method constructs an approximate solution by taking small steps along tangent
      lines to the solution curve.  
      Explain conceptually why using a smaller step size <m>h</m> tends to produce a better
      approximation.  
      Refer to the following SVG illustration showing a single Euler step compared to the true
      solution curve.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="EulerSVGExample">
      <caption>A single Euler step and the exact solution curve.</caption>
      <image source="images/EulerSVGExample" width="75%">
        <description>Euler's method.</description>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Euler’s method replaces the actual solution curve with a straight-line (tangent) approximation
      over a short interval of length <m>h</m>.  
      When <m>h</m> is small, the true solution has little time to “curve away” from the tangent
      line, so the straight segment stays close to the real path.  
      When <m>h</m> is large, the true solution may bend significantly before the method recalculates
      a new slope, causing accumulated error.
    </p>

    <p>
      In the diagram, the blue curve shows the true solution and the red dashed line shows the
      Euler prediction.  
      If the red step were shorter (smaller <m>h</m>), it would end closer to the blue curve.  
      Thus smaller <m>h</m> generally yields a more accurate approximation.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="euler-concept-theory">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Euler’s method uses the slope <m>f(x_i,y_i)</m> to produce the next approximation
      <m>y_{i+1} = y_i + h f(x_i,y_i)</m>.  
      Explain conceptually why the tangent line at a point provides a reasonable approximation to
      the true solution near that point.  
      Why does this idea break down when the slope of the solution curve changes rapidly?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      At each point <m>(x_i,y_i)</m>, the differential equation <m>y' = f(x,y)</m> tells us the exact
      slope of the true solution curve.  
      The tangent line is the linear function with exactly that slope and value at the point.  
      Because a differentiable curve is locally linear, the tangent line matches the actual curve
      extremely well for very small changes in <m>x</m>.  
      Thus taking a short step along the tangent gives a reasonable estimate for the next point.
    </p>

    <p>
      However, if the slope <m>f(x,y)</m> changes rapidly, then the tangent line quickly becomes
      inaccurate.  
      The real solution “bends away” from the tangent line much faster, and the method fails unless
      we reduce the step size <m>h</m>.  
      This explains why Euler’s method performs poorly when the curvature of the true solution is
      large and why decreasing <m>h</m> reduces the error.  

    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="euler-computation-simple">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use Euler’s method with step size <m>h = 0.2</m> to approximate <m>y(0.6)</m> for the
      initial value problem
      <me>
        \frac{dy}{dx} = x + y, \qquad y(0) = 1.
      </me>
      Compute three Euler steps and report the approximate value of <m>y(0.6)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Euler’s method uses the update formulas  
    </p>

    <me>
      x_{n+1} = x_n + h, 
      \qquad 
      y_{n+1} = y_n + h\,f(x_n,y_n),
    </me>

    <p>
      where <m>f(x,y) = x + y</m>.  
      Start with <m>(x_0,y_0) = (0,1)</m> and step size <m>h=0.2</m>.
    </p>

    <p><strong>Step 1:</strong></p>

    <me>
      f(x_0,y_0) = f(0,1) = 0 + 1 = 1.
    </me>

    <me>
      y_1 = 1 + 0.2(1) = 1.2, 
      \qquad 
      x_1 = 0.2.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Step 2:</strong></p>

    <me>
      f(x_1,y_1) = f(0.2,1.2) = 0.2 + 1.2 = 1.4.
    </me>

    <me>
      y_2 = 1.2 + 0.2(1.4) = 1.2 + 0.28 = 1.48,  
      \qquad 
      x_2 = 0.4.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Step 3:</strong></p>

    <me>
      f(x_2,y_2) = f(0.4,1.48) = 0.4 + 1.48 = 1.88.
    </me>

    <md>
      <mrow> y_3 \amp = 1.48 + 0.2(1.88) </mrow>
      <mrow>  \amp  = 1.48 + 0.376 </mrow>
       <mrow> \amp  = 1.856,  </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp x_3 = 0.6. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      Therefore, the Euler approximation for <m>y(0.6)</m> is
    </p>

    <me>
      y(0.6) \approx 1.856.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives17">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
      Analyze sources of numerical error in Euler’s method, including local
      truncation error and the accumulation of global error.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Explain why some numerical methods may be unstable even when the analytic
      solution behaves well.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Compare Euler’s method with higher-order or improved methods in terms of
      accuracy and stability.
            </p>
          </li>

          
    <li><p>
      Evaluate how changing the step size influences numerical stability and 
      identify when a numerical solution may no longer be reliable.
    </p></li>


        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>